"Terray P., Dominiak S.","Indian ocean sea surface temperature and El Niño-southern oscillation: A new perspective",2005,"Journal of Climate","18","9",,"1351","1368",,,10.1175/JCLI3338.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-20444469600&partnerID=40&md5=e170e2c84c3eacef02eaf6d291dd2eeb","Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Université Paris 7, Paris, France; Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4 Place Jussieu, 75252 Paris Cedex 05, France; Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Paris, France","Terray, P., Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Université Paris 7, Paris, France, Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Université Pierre et Marie Curie, 4 Place Jussieu, 75252 Paris Cedex 05, France; Dominiak, S., Laboratoire d'Océanographie Dynamique et de Climatologie, IPSL, Paris, France","Here the 1976-77 climate regime shift that was accompanied by a remarkable change in the lead-lag relationships between Indian Ocean sea surface temperature (SST) and El Niño evolution is shown. After the 1976-77 regime shift, a correlation analysis suggests that southern Indian Ocean SSTs observed during late boreal winter are a key precursor in predicting El Niño evolution as the traditional oceanic heat content anomalies in the equatorial Pacific or zonal wind anomalies over the equatorial western Pacific. The possible physical mechanisms underlying this highly significant statistical relationship are discussed. After the 1976-77 regime shift, southern Indian Ocean SST anomalies produced by Mascarene high pulses during boreal winter trigger coupled air-sea processes in the tropical eastern Indian Ocean during the following seasons. This produces a persistent remote forcing on the Pacific climate system, promoting wind anomalies over the western equatorial Pacific and modulating the regional Hadley cell in the southwest Pacific. These modulations, in turn, excite Rossby waves, which produce quasi-stationary circulation anomalies in the extratropical South Pacific, responsible for the development of the southern branch of the ""horseshoe"" El Niño pattern. The change of the background SST state that occurred in the late 1970s over the Indian Ocean may also explain why ENSO evolution is different before and after the 1976-77 regime shift. These results shed some light on the possible influence of global warming or decadal fluctuations on El Niño evolution through changes in teleconnection patterns between the Indian and Pacific Oceans. © 2005 American Meteorological Society.",,"Correlation methods; Global warming; Water waves; Indian oceans; Teleconnection patterns; Sea level; climate change; El Nino-Southern Oscillation; sea surface temperature; Indian Ocean; oceanic regions; World",,,,,,"Alexander, M.A., Bladé, I., Newman, M., Lanzante, J.R., Lau, N.-C., Scott, J.D., The atmospheric bridge: The influence of ENSO teleconnections on air-sea interaction over the global oceans (2002) J. Climate, 15, pp. 2205-2231; Allan, R.J., Lindesay, J.A., Reason, C.J.C., Multidecadal variability in the climate system over the Indian Ocean region during austral summer (1995) J. Climate, 8, pp. 1853-1873; Allan, R.J., Is there an Indian Ocean dipole, and is it independent of the El Niño-Southern Oscillation? (2001) CLIVAR Exchanges, 6 (3), pp. 18-22. , Coauthors, International CLIVAR Project Office, Southampton, United Kingdom; An, S.-I., Wang, B., Interdecadal change of the structure of the ENSO mode and its impact on the ENSO frequency (2000) J. Climate, 13, pp. 2044-2055; Aoki, S., Yoritaka, M., Masuyama, A., Multidecadal warming of subsurface temperature in the Indian sector of the Southern Ocean (2003) J. Geophys. Res., 108, p. 8081. , doi:10.1029/2000JC000307; Babu, C.B., Joseph, P.V., Post-monsoon sea surface temperature and convection anomalies over Indian and Pacific Oceans (2